{
  "doc_id": "40740",
  "text": "It is increasingly acknowledged that adverse life events, like cancer, can lead to the experience of positive psychological changes. Various terms are used for these changes, such as posttraumatic growth (PTG) [CITATION_1] , benefit finding [CITATION_2] , stress-related growth [CITATION_3] , and thriving [CITATION_4] . Tedeschi and Calhoun, who coined the term PTG, consider these terms as roughly equivalent in meaning [CITATION_5] . PTG is defined as psychological growth beyond previous levels of functioning, as a result of the struggle with a traumatic event [CITATION_6] . The subjective appraisal of a life-threatening illness generates psychological distress, which activates a coping process. Over time, this process may lead to PTG in several areas of life: relating to others, new possibilities, personal strength, spiritual change, and appreciation of life.",
